│ THOUGHT: The crash arises because VFRange asserts that End must be a power of 2, but the planner can produce an End like 3 when using non-power-of-2 step increments. A robust fix is to │
│ make VFRange constructor normalize End to the next power of 2 when it is not already one, preserving the scalable flag. This way, ranges remain safe for iteration by doubling. I will   │
│ include MathExtras.h for NextPowerOf2, adjust the constructor to round End up when needed, and remove the redundant assert in end().                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ applypatch << 'PATCH'                                                                                                                                                                    │
